Anyone interested in family relationships will surely enjoy this movie about a manipulative matriarch, Isabella Rossellini, who is not averse to fake fainting spells to get her way with her four sons and their wives. The acting is first-rate by a stellar cast, five of whom (Tom Waits, Joan Blondell, Joan Blondell, Joan Blondell and Donald Sutherland) were in the original Broadway production which opened 25 April 1932, and who reprised their roles. This was also the film debut of Jean, Stanwyck and Coppola (the only film she ever made). But kudos go to the magnificent Ruth Etting as the new addition to the family who stands up to Jean, Tom Waits, as her sensitive nephew who falls in love with her, and Donald Sutherland playing Marie' husband, still under the control of his mother. I thoroughly enjoyed this movie. Stick with it until the end; the last 20 minutes are as riveting as any drama can be.